        "text": "*[Bug 19009] tools::file_path_sans_ext() does not recognise file extension of names that end in a dot.*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19009>\n\nElin Waring (<mailto:elin.waring@gmail.com|elin.waring@gmail.com>) changed:\n\n           What    |Removed                     |Added\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n                 CC|                            |elin.waring@gmail.com\n\n--- Comment #1 from Elin Waring (<mailto:elin.waring@gmail.com|elin.waring@gmail.com>) ---\nFrom what I can tell, the original version of what becamse file_sans_ext() was\nintroduced 24 years ago\n\n<https:\/\/github.com\/r-devel\/r-svn\/commit\/49fbaabde9a0d7869d9253a00530e45efab39ff3>\n\nI think that when `file_ext()` was added, 17 years ago, it indeed used a\ndifferent regex. (and `sub()` rather than `regexpr()`. It assumes that the last\nperiod in the filename indicates the start of a file extension \n\n\n&gt; file_path_sans_ext returns the file paths without extensions (and the leading dot). (Only purely alphanumeric extensions are recognized.)\n\n`file_path_sans-ext` essentially assumes that a file extension can be\nidentified by finding a single `.` and removing text from there onward.  When\nthe name is something like \"ab..txt.txt\" it returns \"ab..txt\".   \n\nIn some older file systems a name with \"..\" is not valid (See\n[<https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Filename>] for more details). \n\nGiven how much more unrestricted file names have become in the last 24 years, I\nthink it would make sense to add a sentence or two to the Details of the file\nutilities help describing the different assumptions.",
        "username": "r-bugs notifier",
        "icons": {
            "emoji": ":robot_face:"
        },
